cy analysis, and participant observation at two PGD centers in the United Kingdom, Born and Made provides an in-depth sociological examination of the competing moral obligations that define the experience of PGD. Among the many novel findings of this pathbreaking ethnography of reproductive biomedicine is the prominence of uncertainty and ambivalence among PGD patients and professionals--a finding characteristic of the emerging "biosociety," in which scientific progress is inherently paradoxical and contradictory. In contrast to much of the speculative futurology that defines this field, Born and Made provides a timely and revealing case study of the on-the-ground decision-making that shapes technological assistance to human heredity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aGenetic Diseases, InbornvdiagnosiszGreat Britain. 0aMEDICALvGynecology and ampxObstetrics. 0aPreimplantation genetic diagnosisvMoral and ethical aspects. 0aPreimplantation genetic diagnosisxMoral and ethical aspects. 0aPreimplantation genetic diagnosisxSocial aspectsxGreat Britain. 0aPreimplantation genetic diagnosisxSocial aspectszGreat Britain. 0aPreimplantation genetic diagnosiszGreat Britainvethics. 0aSocial sciencesvSociologyvGeneral. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh1 aRoberts, Celia, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044250240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781400835423zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400835423423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400835423.jpg  a978-3-11-044250-2  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEB